




             DK PATCH is a patch librarian for the SIEL DK-600 and the
         SIEL EX-600 polyphonic synthesizers.  This is the first in a
         series of shareware patch librarians / editors for all the
         "orphan" keyboards in the world. The "orphan" keyboards are
         all the ones that have been forgotten by software developers
         of the world. It is a fact that the Casio CZ series and
         Yamaha DX series keyboards are not the only keyboards in the
         world (Although software companies would have you believe
         this). The basic patch librarians will be put in the public
         domain for easy access, while the full-fledged editors (with
         more sofisticated patch options) will be available for $10
         along with a disk to put the software on. An in-depth manual
         will also be sent along with the software. EX-600 owners will
         be in heaven with the editor!!!!!

             Here is a list of the files in the ARC file:
         PATCH1_0.BAS
         PATCHGET.BAS
         MERGE.BAS
         FACTORY.SET
         DKPATCH.DOC

             All of the programs started out in Megamax C, but one day
         with the new GFA BASIC from GFA Systemtechnik changed my
         mind. The constant recompiling with C is a real drag. Between
         the nice editor, the incredible execution speed, and having
         an interpeter to work with again to speed up debugging, there
         doesn't appear to be a real reason to go back to C. The
         execution speed is very close to C or PASCAL, without the
         headaches. A compiler is due shortly, and if it is as good as
         the interpeter, you will be able to throw away all your C
         compilers. (Thank God for small favors). If you haven't
         worked with GFA yet you are in for a real treat. The run-time
         program from GFA is public domain and available on most of
         the major BBS's.

             PATCH1_0.BAS is the patch librarian. It is very straight
         forward with drop down menues and dialog boxes guiding your
         way. Follow the prompts and you should not have any problems
         at all.  The only problem that occurs in the librarian that
         is less noticable in the editor is when to press the infamous
         "95/ENTER" combination on the DK. This turns on and off the
         record mode, which also enables and disables the
         System-exclusive operations. When dumping to the dk you will
         see a very short blink in the patch number, and a change in
         the number if you so desired. If Dumping to the DK doesn't
         work, press 95/ENTER and try it again. That should cure the
         problems.
             Since there is no way to tell the DK to send a patch by
         way of the SYS_ex_codes, you have to activate the sends from
         the DK. The alert boxes will tell you what to do.
             It is necessary to put a folder on your work disk called
         "DK6". This is where the patches will be stored. After the
         session is over, move these to another folder , as to have
         room in the directory for all the files ( At 95 files per











         patch set, you will fill up the main directory VERY quickly,
         so folders are your only hope) Be sure to have your patches
         in the DK saved on tape till you get used to using DKPATCH.
             You will notice when getting info from the DK numbers
         scroll by on the screen. These are the MIDI codes sent to the
         computer from the DK. They were there for debugging purposes
         and I decided to leave them there. You can learn a lot by
         keeping track of these, especially at the beginning of
         getting patches from the DK. The numbers after the first
         alert box is the data left in the midi buffer of the ST which
         has to be cleaned out before the patch info can be recieved
         properly.  Try hitting a few keys before "OK'ing" the first
         alert box, and you will see the midi key codes (note values,
         key on, key off, velocity values, etc) when you click on the
         ok box.

             PATCHGET.BAS is a short utility designed to transfer all
         95 voices from the Dk to disk as painlessly as possible.
         Again, follow the prompts, starting at voice 00 and go up in
         order to make it as easy as possible. Be sure that the "DK6"
         folder is in drive A and is empty when you start. Just press
         the return key on the ST at all times. the program does the
         rest. It will supply the filenames it gives for a later
         reason. Let it do it's thing with little intervention.
             MERGE.BAS is use to combine all the files created by
         PATCHGET.BAS into a 95 voice SET for full memory dump to the
         DK. Here again it does all the work for you. The sloppy
         screen display during execution was left alone to tell you it
         is working. The resulting .SET file can be renamed after the
         utility is done. These two utilities were put together
         quickly to make life easier on the user, and minimal time was
         spent to make them "professional". The editor and librarian
         are a different story as you will see. After using the
         librarian you will see why these utilities were created.
             FACTORY.SET is the factory installed sounds when the DK
         is new. It saves loading them from tape.
             If there are any questions on operation or other midi
         questions drop me a letter at the address in the "About..."
         boxes, or leave me email on GENIE. my address is DONT

             I hope this program is useful to you, and hope it gets
         you to decide to upgrade to the full editor.  Future projects
         include a couple of drum machine librarian/editors (wait til
         you see the editor!!), And quite a few different synths are
         on the list for librarians and editors. I am looking forward
         to your comments and suggestions.

                  Dr. Don's Software...for the midi-minded musician.













